===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|see|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|sæ|sǣ|lang=ang}} 'sea, lake', from {{proto|Germanic|saiwiz}} (compare West Frisian {{term|see|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|zee|lang=nl}}, German {{term|See|lang=de}}), probably from {{proto|Indo-European|sh₂ei-u̯o}}- 'to be fierce, afflict' (compare Latin {{term|saevus|lang=la}} 'wild, fierce', Tocharian {{term|saiwe|lang=txb}} 'itch', Latvian {{term|sievs|lang=lt}}, {{term|sivs|sīvs|lang=lt}} 'sharp, biting').<ref>Vladimir Orel, ''A Handbook of Germanic Etymology'', s.v. "saiwiz" (Louden, Netherlands: Brill, 2003), 314.</ref> More to [[sore]].

